                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\"><placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>, <date>21<hi rend=\"sup\">st</hi>\n                    Octr. 1866</date></p>\n            <p>My dear <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">At length I enjoy a day's ease from toil and of<lb/> comparative\n                coolness, leaving me sufficient time and<lb/> energy after the exhausting and\n                incessant heat of over<lb/> five months duration to drop you a few lines; not<lb/>\n                in answer to your last, for I have mislaid your letter,<lb/> put in some safe place,\n                which has escaped my memory.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">If the situation at <placeName>Savannah</placeName> did not\n                materially<lb/> interfere with your high position as the leader and<lb/> exponent of\n                orthodoxy, that is, if the acceptance of it<lb/> did not, in a measure shelve you,\n                by consigning you,<lb/> to so comparatively insignificant a sphere, I would<lb/> be\n                the first to advise you to quit <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, and<lb/>\n                honorably retire to a spot where your influence might<lb/> still be felt, and when\n                the duties would be to <hi rend=\"underline\">you</hi><lb/> light and easy, and above\n                all a resting place to<lb/> breathe in and enjoy yourself after your laborious\n                and<lb/> toilsome career. Could you not manage to issue the<lb/> Occident there?\n                That you should have a disinclination<lb/> to leave <placeName>Pa.</placeName> when\n                your world-wide reputation</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3ft8f52x/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
