              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3ft8f52x/manifest/annotation/p4",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>4</p>\n            <p>particularly of the second day <add>מקיל ולא מחמיר</add> which I had been<lb/> taught\n                to believe had been kept in <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName> from the days<lb/> of\n                    <persName>Ezra</persName> has no such historical basis, but dates from a<lb/>\n                very recent period; and, to my astonishment, I learned for<lb/> the first time that\n                on that day, the common daily prayers<lb/> are said in\n                    <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>, and not those for the festival.<lb/> I had\n                heard before that some of the <add>חכמה המשנה והתלמוד</add> from the <placeName>Holy\n                    City</placeName><lb/> came to Synagogue in <placeName>London</placeName> on\n                    <add>לא אלמן ישראל</add> with their Tephillin on.<lb/> Really, therefore if our\n                orthodox guides do not bestir them<lb/>selves and clean up the obscurities which\n                envelop our<lb/> minhagim, particularly their origin and history, much<lb/> will be\n                swept away which should be retained. A book<lb/> has been in my library for years,\n                called <add>מעשי דעלמא</add>, which<lb/> curiosity induced me lately to peruse, as\n                it is frequently quoted<lb/> by <persName>Zumy<add>?</add></persName> in his Gottes\n                dienstliche Vorträge, and not alone the<lb/> reasoning of the author, but the\n                support it receives from<lb/>\n                <del>dist</del> quotations of distinguished writers, truly orthodox,<lb/> have\n                entirely shaken my faith in the Rabbinism of<lb/> the middle ages, little as I\n                believed in it before. I had<lb/> often begun to read this volume, but it seemed to\n                be exclusively<lb/> directed against the stassidim<add>?</add>, and so it did\n                not<lb/> interest me, whereas now I am going thro' it carefully.</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3ft8f52x/canvas/p4"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
