              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3ft8f52x/manifest/annotation/p5",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">5</p>\n            <p>It seems that the converse of <add>טוב רע מאח</add> was the rule of<lb/> our guides\n                in the middle ages, and that either they did not<lb/> understand the sayings and\n                doings of their revered predecessors,<lb/> the <add>אם אמת הדבר</add> who view large\n                souled and enlightened men,<lb/>\n                <del>and</del> but introduced a sort of asceticism into Judaism, public &amp;<lb/>\n                private, or they assumed an authority which modern research<lb/> questions, and\n                refuses any longer to tolerate. Do not imagine<lb/> by my writing in this strain\n                that I am going to turn ultra<lb/> Reformer. The second days are still kept here,\n                and the Synagogue<lb/> attended by a few, just sufficient to make minyan. With\n                the<lb/> exception of five Jewish stores, and the remainder are closed<lb/> by my\n                people on <del>that day</del> the <date>Sabbath</date>, tho' among them are rabid\n                Reformers<lb/> who keep aloof from the Synag: except on on <date>Rosh\n                    Hashanah</date> and<lb/>\n                <date>Kippoor</date>, until certain modifications in the Ritual and public<lb/>\n                worship are sanctioned by me. I must yield, or extremes<lb/> will be resorted to,\n                whose consequences would imperil the conserv-<lb/>ation of important and fundamental\n                things. What conscientious<lb/> pangs might have been spared men struggling like\n                myself to<lb/> preserve the unity of formula in our worship had we been<lb/> backed\n                by an orthodox Synod of learned &amp; enlightened<lb/> Rabbis, prepared to direct\n                claims for changes into a channel</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3ft8f52x/canvas/p5"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
